            "text": "\n\nEgyptian Numerals and the Number Five\n\nAncient Egyptian civilization, known for its enigmatic pyramids and mummies, also contributed significantly to numeral systems. Around 3000 BCE, the Egyptians devised a numeration system based on tens, which was inscribed in their renowned hieroglyphs. Unlike modern place-value systems, their numerals did not denote position but were additive in nature.\n\nTheir numeral system prominently included symbols for one and multiples of ten up to a million. Notably, the number five was represented by a hieroglyph resembling a single upright stroke, indicating the significance of human anatomy in the formulation of numerical symbols. These symbols were repetitively used to represent numbers in multiples of ten.\n\nFor example, the number 'five' itself was simply denoted by the respective singular symbol. However, when it came to writing the number fifty, the Egyptians would place the symbol for ten, a representation of a cattle hobble, five times consecutively. This additive system reflected not just their practical approach to counting but also their cultural aesthetic in integrating everyday objects into their writing.\n\nA fascinating aspect of Egyptian numeration was their concept of zero, represented by the symbol 'nfr' signifying beauty, which also doubled to denote the base level in architecture drawings. Moreover, when they needed to depict fractions, they mostly used a system of unit fractions, adding to the complexity of Egyptian mathematics. The fractions were written as combinations of symbols, including one that resembled a mouth, further showcasing their creativity in numeral depiction.\n\nThe administrative and accounting texts, typically written on papyrus and ostraca, used a more simplified version of numerals known as hieratic script. This script used individual signs for numbers 1 to 9 and multiples of tens and hundreds. For large numbers, the hieratic script proved to be a ground-breaking 